\begin_layout Standard
Determining the coefficients in the linear combination of basis vectors
 that sum to a given vector is big business in engineering and the sciences.
 This problem is generally aided by careful choice of basis vectors (see
 Legendre Polynomials, Fourier Series, and Finite Element Methods, for example).
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
TODO: Add references to this book(?) and engineering texts 
\end_layout

\end_inset

But what makes one set of basis vectors better than another? To get some
 idea, suppose we have an arbitrary basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}=\{\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{2},\ldots,\mathbf{b}_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 for an inner product space 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and an arbitrary vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 The problem stated mathematically is to find coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},a_{2},\ldots,a_{n}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{v}=a_{1}\mathbf{b}_{1}+a_{2}\mathbf{b}_{2}+\cdots+a_{n}\mathbf{b}_{n}.\label{eq:the-coefficient-problem}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $V=\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, this is the vector form of a linear system.
 It can be solved by row reduction.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $V\neq\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, it is less obvious how to solve.
 Using coordinate vectors (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Coordinate-Vectors"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) is one way to proceed, but since 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is an inner product space, we can leverage the inner product to turn the
 problem into a question of solving a linear system instead.
 To start, can you show that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mathbf{w},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle=\langle\mathbf{w},\mathbf{b}_{2}\rangle=\cdots=\langle\mathbf{w},\mathbf{b}_{n}\rangle=0$
\end_inset

 for any vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}\in V$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}=\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

? Answer on page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "ans:zero-inner-products"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Only the zero vector is orthogonal to (has inner product zero with) every
 vector in a basis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking the inner product with each basis vector on both sides of (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:the-coefficient-problem"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) produces the following linear system.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\langle\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle & =\langle a_{1}\mathbf{b}_{1}+a_{2}\mathbf{b}_{2}+\cdots+a_{n}\mathbf{b}_{n},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle\nonumber \\
\langle\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}_{2}\rangle & =\langle a_{1}\mathbf{b}_{1}+a_{2}\mathbf{b}_{2}+\cdots+a_{n}\mathbf{b}_{n},\mathbf{b}_{2}\rangle\nonumber \\
 & \vdots\nonumber \\
\langle\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}_{n}\rangle & =\langle a_{1}\mathbf{b}_{1}+a_{2}\mathbf{b}_{2}+\cdots+a_{n}\mathbf{b}_{n},\mathbf{b}_{n}\rangle\label{eq:coefficients-inner-products}
\end{align}

\end_inset

and by inner product space properties 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "enu:inner-product-preserve-sum"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "enu:inner-product-preserve-scalar-mult"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\langle\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle & =a_{1}\langle\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle+a_{2}\langle\mathbf{b}_{2},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle+\cdots+a_{n}\langle\mathbf{b}_{n},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle\\
\langle\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}_{2}\rangle & =a_{1}\langle\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{2}\rangle+a_{2}\langle\mathbf{b}_{2},\mathbf{b}_{2}\rangle+\cdots+a_{n}\langle\mathbf{b}_{n},\mathbf{b}_{2}\rangle\\
 & \vdots\\
\langle\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}_{n}\rangle & =a_{1}\langle\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{n}\rangle+a_{2}\langle\mathbf{b}_{2},\mathbf{b}_{n}\rangle+\cdots+a_{n}\langle\mathbf{b}_{n},\mathbf{b}_{n}\rangle
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and in matrix format
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
\langle\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle & \langle\mathbf{b}_{2},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle & \cdots & \langle\mathbf{b}_{n},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle\\
\langle\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{2}\rangle & \langle\mathbf{b}_{2},\mathbf{b}_{2}\rangle & \cdots & \langle\mathbf{b}_{n},\mathbf{b}_{2}\rangle\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
\langle\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{n}\rangle & \langle\mathbf{b}_{2},\mathbf{b}_{n}\rangle & \cdots & \langle\mathbf{b}_{n},\mathbf{b}_{n}\rangle
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
a_{1}\\
a_{2}\\
\vdots\\
a_{n}
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{c}
\langle\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle\\
\langle\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}_{2}\rangle\\
\vdots\\
\langle\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}_{n}\rangle
\end{array}\right].\label{eq:coefficients-matrix-format}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

No matter the vector and no matter the basis, this problem is reduced to
 solving this linear system of equations, a problem that we have studied
 extensively!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If that were all there were to it, though, this method would hardly be better
 than using coordinate vectors.
 This section began by suggesting that careful choice of basis would help.
 Since the process of row reduction involves producing zeros above and below
 the pivots, starting with some zeros in the matrix would be beneficial.
 For example, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

 were zero, it would put zeros in the 
\begin_inset Formula $1,2$
\end_inset

-entry and the 
\begin_inset Formula $2,1$
\end_inset

-entry.
 More generally, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mathbf{b}_{i},\mathbf{b}_{j}\rangle$
\end_inset

 were zero, it would put zeros in the 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j$
\end_inset

-entry and the 
\begin_inset Formula $j,i$
\end_inset

-entry.
 The more orthogonal pairs of basis vectors (zero inner products between
 basis vectors) the better.
 Thinking greedily, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mathbf{b}_{i},\mathbf{b}_{j}\rangle=0$
\end_inset

 for all pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

, the system reads 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
\langle\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle & 0 & \cdots & 0\\
0 & \langle\mathbf{b}_{2},\mathbf{b}_{2}\rangle & \cdots & 0\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
0 & 0 & \cdots & \langle\mathbf{b}_{n},\mathbf{b}_{n}\rangle
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
a_{1}\\
a_{2}\\
\vdots\\
a_{n}
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{c}
\langle\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle\\
\langle\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}_{2}\rangle\\
\vdots\\
\langle\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}_{n}\rangle
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

and has solution 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}=\frac{\langle\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle}{\langle\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}=\frac{\langle\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}_{2}\rangle}{\langle\mathbf{b}_{2},\mathbf{b}_{2}\rangle}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $\ldots$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}=\frac{\langle\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}_{n}\rangle}{\langle\mathbf{b}_{n},\mathbf{b}_{n}\rangle}$
\end_inset

.
 Better yet, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle=\langle\mathbf{b}_{2},\mathbf{b}_{2}\rangle=\cdots=\langle\mathbf{b}_{n},\mathbf{b}_{n}\rangle=1$
\end_inset

, the solution is simply 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}=\langle\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}=\langle\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $\ldots$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}=\langle\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}_{n}\rangle$
\end_inset

â€”the coefficients are simply the inner products of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 with each of the basis vectors.
\end_layout

