\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
The first vector of the orthogonal basis is taken as the first vector of
 the original basis.
 The second vector of the orthogonal basis is taken as the second vector
 of the original basis minus a particular vector.
 The third vector of the orthogonal basis is taken as the third vector of
 the original basis minus two particular vectors.
 But what vectors ought to be subtracted? A clever observation will answer
 the question.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given any vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{2}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left\langle \mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{2}-\frac{\langle\mathbf{b}_{2},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle}{\langle\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle}\mathbf{b}_{1}\right\rangle  & =\left\langle \mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{2}\right\rangle -\left\langle \mathbf{b}_{1},\frac{\langle\mathbf{b}_{2},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle}{\langle\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle}\mathbf{b}_{1}\right\rangle \\
 & =\left\langle \mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{2}\right\rangle -\frac{\langle\mathbf{b}_{2},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle}{\langle\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle}\left\langle \mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{1}\right\rangle \\
 & =\left\langle \mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{2}\right\rangle -\langle\mathbf{b}_{2},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle\\
 & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{2}-\frac{\langle\mathbf{b}_{2},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle}{\langle\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle}\mathbf{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

 are always orthogonal (even if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{2}$
\end_inset

 are not).
 And this applies in any inner product space, not just 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The term 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\langle\mathbf{b}_{2},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle}{\langle\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle}\mathbf{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

 is called the component of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{2}$
\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

 direction or the projection of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{2}$
\end_inset

 onto 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

, and is often denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{proj}_{\mathbf{b}_{1}}\mathbf{b}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Subtracting this term from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{2}$
\end_inset

 removes this component from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{2}$
\end_inset

, leaving only the component of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{2}$
\end_inset

 orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, this can be seen geometrically:
\end_layout

