\begin_layout Standard
Given a set of three vectors, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{2},\mathbf{b}_{3}$
\end_inset

, they can be orthogonalized by extending the process to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Its components in the directions of both 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{2}-\frac{\langle\mathbf{b}_{2},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle}{\langle\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle}\mathbf{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

 will need to be subtracted.
 Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}_{1}=\mathbf{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}_{2}=\mathbf{b}_{2}-\text{proj}_{\mathbf{w}_{1}}\mathbf{b}_{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}_{3}=\mathbf{b}_{3}-\text{proj}_{\mathbf{w}_{1}}\mathbf{b}_{3}-\text{proj}_{\mathbf{w}_{2}}\mathbf{b}_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 For larger sets, the process continues recursively.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathbf{w}_{1} & =\mathbf{b}_{1}\nonumber \\
\mathbf{w}_{j} & =\mathbf{b}_{j}-\text{proj}_{\mathbf{w}_{1}}\mathbf{b}_{j}-\text{proj}_{\mathbf{w}_{2}}\mathbf{b}_{j}-\cdots-\text{proj}_{\mathbf{w}_{j-1}}\mathbf{b}_{j},\quad j=2,3,\ldots,n.\label{eq:orthogonalization}
\end{align}

\end_inset

The process as described by (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:orthogonalization"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) is called Gram-Schmidt orthogonalization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A couple details have thus far been overlooked.
 The discussion at the beginning of the section establishes that (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:the-coefficient-problem"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) implies (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:coefficients-matrix-format"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), but what we have been relying on is the converse, that (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:coefficients-matrix-format"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) implies (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:the-coefficient-problem"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 Following our steps backward, the same properties of inner product spaces
 that gave us that (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:coefficients-inner-products"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) implies (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:coefficients-matrix-format"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) work in reverse, giving us (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:coefficients-matrix-format"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) implies (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:coefficients-inner-products"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 However, the implication from (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:coefficients-inner-products"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) to (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:the-coefficient-problem"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) is not as straightforward.
 Assuming (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:coefficients-inner-products"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) we need to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}=a_{1}\mathbf{b}_{1}+a_{2}\mathbf{b}_{2}+\cdots+a_{n}\mathbf{b}_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Moving everything to the lefthand side in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:coefficients-inner-products"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

),
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\langle\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle-\langle a_{1}\mathbf{b}_{1}+a_{2}\mathbf{b}_{2}+\cdots+a_{n}\mathbf{b}_{n},\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle & =0\\
\langle\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}_{2}\rangle-\langle a_{1}\mathbf{b}_{1}+a_{2}\mathbf{b}_{2}+\cdots+a_{n}\mathbf{b}_{n},\mathbf{b}_{2}\rangle & =0\\
 & \vdots\\
\langle\mathbf{v},\mathbf{b}_{n}\rangle-\langle a_{1}\mathbf{b}_{1}+a_{2}\mathbf{b}_{2}+\cdots+a_{n}\mathbf{b}_{n},\mathbf{b}_{n}\rangle & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\langle\mathbf{v}-(a_{1}\mathbf{b}_{1}+a_{2}\mathbf{b}_{2}+\cdots+a_{n}\mathbf{b}_{n}),\mathbf{b}_{1}\rangle & =0\\
\langle\mathbf{v}-(a_{1}\mathbf{b}_{1}+a_{2}\mathbf{b}_{2}+\cdots+a_{n}\mathbf{b}_{n}),\mathbf{b}_{2}\rangle & =0\\
 & \vdots\\
\langle\mathbf{v}-(a_{1}\mathbf{b}_{1}+a_{2}\mathbf{b}_{2}+\cdots+a_{n}\mathbf{b}_{n}),\mathbf{b}_{n}\rangle & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}-(a_{1}\mathbf{b}_{1}+a_{2}\mathbf{b}_{2}+\cdots+a_{n}\mathbf{b}_{n})$
\end_inset

 is orthogonal to each basis vector.
 As shown in 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

zero inner products
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "ans:zero-inner-products"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, this means 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}-(a_{1}\mathbf{b}_{1}+a_{2}\mathbf{b}_{2}+\cdots+a_{n}\mathbf{b}_{n})=\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

 and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}=a_{1}\mathbf{b}_{1}+a_{2}\mathbf{b}_{2}+\cdots+a_{n}\mathbf{b}_{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The span of the orthogonalized vectors is the same as the span of the original
 vectors.
 This is an important feature of the process if you are orthogonalizing
 the basis of a subspace.
 Even more is true, though: 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{span}\{\mathbf{w}_{1},\mathbf{w}_{2},\ldots,\mathbf{w}_{j}\}=\text{span}\{\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{2},\ldots,\mathbf{b}_{j}\}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,2,\ldots,n$
\end_inset

.
 This can be justified by induction.
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{span}\{\mathbf{w}_{1}\}=\text{span}\{\mathbf{b}_{1}\}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}_{1}=\mathbf{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

 so the claim is true for 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1$
\end_inset

.
 Now suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{span}\{\mathbf{w}_{1},\mathbf{w}_{2},\ldots,\mathbf{w}_{j-1}\}=\text{span}\{\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{2},\ldots,\mathbf{b}_{j-1}\}$
\end_inset

 for some arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $j\geq2$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

